James assigned Dietz et al. 2007 for a Climate Change Economics class, focusing on the intersection of economics and ethics in climate policy analysis. The reading discusses the need to consider various ethical perspectives beyond standard welfare economics, emphasizing intergenerational justice, risk, and distribution among individuals. It highlights the complexity of climate change challenges, advocating for a careful examination of ethical issues to guide economic analyses. The reading underscores the fundamental importance of future generations in policy-making and critiques the reliance on markets to address all ethical concerns in climate change. Multiple-choice questions based on the reading were provided to assess students' understanding of key concepts and ethical considerations in climate economics.
